{"title_page": "Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1668)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n__NOTOC__\n[[File:Map Peace of Aix la Chapelle (English).png|thumb|350px|Areas gained and returned by Louis XIV in Aix, 1668]]\n\nThe '''Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle''' or '''Aachen''' ended the [[War of Devolution]] between France and Spain. It was signed on 2 May 1668 in [[Aachen]] ({{lang-fr|Aix-la-Chapelle}}). Spain acceded on 7 May 1669.\n\nThe treaty was mediated and guaranteed by the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]] of the [[Dutch Republic]], [[England]] and [[Sweden]] at the '''First Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle'''. By the terms of the treaty, [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]] returned three cities, [[Cambrai]] (Kamerijk), [[Aire-sur-la-Lys|Aire]] (Ari\u00ebn aan de Leie), and [[Saint-Omer]] (Sint-Omaars) to Spain.<ref name=Phillipson>Phillipson (1916), p. 222.</ref> He also returned the province of [[Franche-Comt\u00e9]].<ref name=Phillipson/> On the other hand, he kept [[Armenti\u00e8res]] (Armentiers), [[Bergues]] (Sint-Winoksbergen), [[Charleroi]], [[Courtrai]] (Kortrijk), [[Douai]] (Dowaai), [[Veurne|Furnes]] (Veurne), [[Lille]] (Rijsel), [[Oudenarde]] (Oudenaarde, Audenarde), and [[Tournai]]  (Doornik).<ref name=Phillipson/> [[Lille]], [[Armenti\u00e8res]], [[Bergues]] and [[Douai]] were considered essential to reinforce France's vulnerable northern border and remain French to this day, while the retention of [[Tournai]], [[Oudenarde]], [[Courtrai]], [[Veurne]], [[Binche]], [[Charleroi]] and [[Ath]] greatly facilitated potential future offensives against the [[Dutch Republic]].\n\nThe treaty left to France all its conquests in [[Flanders]] in 1667. This was a vague provision; after the [[Peace of Nijmegen]] (1679), Louis XIV took advantage of it to occupy a number of villages and towns he adjudged to be dependencies of the cities and territories acquired in 1668.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of treaties]]\n*[[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Aix-la-Chapelle, Congresses of |volume=1 |page=450}}\n*{{cite book|title=Termination Of War And Treaties Of Peace|first=Coleman|last=Phillipson|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange|orig-year= First published 1916|date= 2010|isbn=1584778601}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last= du Mont|first= Jean, Baron de Carlscroon|author-link= Jean Dumont (publicist)|title= Corps universel diplomatique du droit des gens|location= Amsterdam, The Hague|date= 1726\u20131731|oclc= 558450542}} Also {{oclc|22014082}} and {{oclc|6967152}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192313/http://www.ieg-mainz.de/likecms/index.php?site=transliteration.htm&dir=&treaty=225 Transcription of the treaty (in French, IEG Mainz)]\n* {{CathEncy|wstitle=Aachen}}\n\n[[Category:History of Aachen]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of the Ancien R\u00e9gime|Aix-la-Chapelle, Treaty of (1668)]]\n[[Category:Peace treaties of Spain|Aix-la-Chapelle, Treaty of (1668)]]\n[[Category:Treaties of the Spanish Empire|Aix-la-Chapelle, Treaty of (1668)]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Spain relations]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic conferences in Germany]]\n[[Category:17th-century diplomatic conferences]]\n[[Category:1668 treaties]]\n[[Category:1668 in France]]\n[[Category:1668 in Spain]]\n\n\n{{France-hist-stub}}\n{{Netherlands-hist-stub}}\n{{Spain-hist-stub}}\n{{Sweden-hist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n__NOTOC__\n[[File:Map Peace of Aix la Chapelle (English).png|thumb|350px|Areas gained and returned by Louis XIV in Aix, 1668]]\n\nThe '''Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle''' or '''Aachen''' ended the [[War of Devolution]] between France and Spain. It was signed on 2 May 1668 in [[Aachen]] ({{lang-fr|Aix-la-Chapelle}}). Spain acceded on 7 May 1669.\n\nThe treaty was mediated and guaranteed by the [[Triple Alliance (1668)|Triple Alliance]] of England, the [[Dutch Republic]] and Sweden at the '''First Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle'''. France was forced to abandon its war against the [[Spanish Netherlands]].\n[[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]] returned three cities, [[Cambrai]] (Kamerijk), [[Aire-sur-la-Lys|Aire]] (Ari\u00ebn aan de Leie), and [[Saint-Omer]] (Sint-Omaars) to Spain.<ref name=Phillipson>Phillipson (1916), p. 222.</ref> Louis XIV also had to return the province of [[Franche-Comt\u00e9]].<ref name=Phillipson/> Louis XIV was however allowed to keep [[Armenti\u00e8res]] (Armentiers), [[Bergues]] (Sint-Winoksbergen), [[Charleroi]], [[Courtrai]] (Kortrijk), [[Douai]] (Dowaai), [[Veurne|Furnes]] (Veurne), [[Lille]] (Rijsel), [[Oudenarde]] (Oudenaarde, Audenarde), and [[Tournai]] (Doornik).<ref name=Phillipson/>\n\nThe treaty left to France all its conquests in [[Flanders]] in 1667. This was a vague provision; after the [[Peace of Nijmegen]] (1679), Louis XIV took advantage of it to occupy a number of villages and towns he adjudged to be dependencies of the cities and territories acquired in 1668.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of treaties]]\n*[[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Aix-la-Chapelle, Congresses of |volume=1 |page=450}}\n*{{cite book|title=Termination Of War And Treaties Of Peace|first=Coleman|last=Phillipson|publisher=The Lawbook Exchange|orig-year= First published 1916|date= 2010|isbn=1584778601}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last= du Mont|first= Jean, Baron de Carlscroon|author-link= Jean Dumont (publicist)|title= Corps universel diplomatique du droit des gens|location= Amsterdam, The Hague|date= 1726\u20131731|oclc= 558450542}} Also {{oclc|22014082}} and {{oclc|6967152}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140102192313/http://www.ieg-mainz.de/likecms/index.php?site=transliteration.htm&dir=&treaty=225 Transcription of the treaty (in French, IEG Mainz)]\n* {{CathEncy|wstitle=Aachen}}\n\n[[Category:History of Aachen]]\n[[