{"title_page": "Ronnie Irani", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Ronnie Irani\n|               image = Ronnie Irani.jpg\n|             country = England\n|            fullname = Ronald Charles Irani \n|            nickname = Reggie \n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1971|10|26|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], [[Lancashire]], England\n|            heightft = 6\n|          heightinch = 4\n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Right arm [[Medium pace bowling|medium]]\n|       international = true\n|   internationalspan = 1996\u20132003\n|       testdebutdate = 6 June\n|       testdebutyear = 1996\n|    testdebutagainst = India\n|             testcap = 577\n|        lasttestdate = 22 August\n|        lasttestyear = 1999\n|     lasttestagainst = New Zealand\n|        odidebutdate = 23 May\n|        odidebutyear = 1996\n|     odidebutagainst = India\n|              odicap = 137\n|         lastodidate = 26 February\n|         lastodiyear = 2003\n|      lastodiagainst = India\n|            odishirt = 15\n|               club1 = [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]\n|               year1 = 1990\u20131993\n|               club2 = [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]]\n|               year2 = 1994\u20132007\n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|            matches1 = 3\n|               runs1 = 86\n|            bat avg1 = 17.20\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 41\n|         deliveries1 = 192\n|            wickets1 = 3\n|           bowl avg1 = 37.33\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 1/22\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 2/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches2 = 31\n|               runs2 = 360\n|            bat avg2 = 14.40\n|           100s/50s2 = 0/1\n|          top score2 = 53\n|         deliveries2 = 1,283\n|            wickets2 = 24\n|           bowl avg2 = 41.20\n|            fivefor2 = 1\n|             tenfor2 = 0\n|       best bowling2 = 5/26\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 6/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 232\n|               runs3 = 13,472\n|            bat avg3 = 41.58\n|           100s/50s3 = 28/72\n|          top score3 = 218\n|         deliveries3 = 20,389\n|            wickets3 = 339\n|           bowl avg3 = 29.51\n|            fivefor3 = 9\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 6/71\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 79/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 315\n|               runs4 = 7,733\n|            bat avg4 = 30.93\n|           100s/50s4 = 7/46\n|          top score4 = 158[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries4 = 10,453\n|            wickets4 = 309\n|           bowl avg4 = 25.22\n|            fivefor4 = 4\n|             tenfor4 = 0\n|       best bowling4 = 5/26\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 83/\u2013\n|                date = 19 April\n|                year = 2017\n|              source = http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/15403.html Cricinfo\n}}\n'''Ronald Charles  \"Ronnie\" Irani''' (born 26 October 1971<!---in 1971 Leigh was then still part of Lancashire--->) is a former England [[cricket]]er who played Tests and ODIs for England. He played only three [[Test cricket|Tests]] for [[English cricket team|England]], with decidedly mixed success, but found a niche in [[One Day International]]s, where he gained much praise for his performances.\n\nHe spent most of his career at [[Essex County Cricket Club]], latterly as [[captain (cricket)|captain]], after starting at [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]. He is of [[Irani (India)|Irani]] descent, the Iranis being a community of [[Persian people|Persian]] [[Zoroastrian]]s who immigrated to India during the [[British Raj]].\n\nIrani was a genuine [[all-rounder]] until a knee injury in 2003 forced him to stop bowling and play as a specialist batsman. The recurring nature of this injury led to Irani being forced to retire from [[first-class cricket]] in June 2007. At Essex, Irani helped bring through promising players such as [[Alastair Cook]] (England Captain) and [[Ravinder Bopara]] (England Player) as well as winning two major One-Day Titles. Professionally he scored over 20,000 runs and took more than 650 wickets during his career.\n\nHe announced his retirement from first-class cricket at the end of the 2007 season.\n\n==Personal life==\nIrani's father Jimmy Irani arrived in Bolton from Bombay in 1961 to play a summer's club cricket. During that summer he met 16-year-old Lancastrian Anne Main. The two married and had a son, Ronnie. Jimmy Irani was an enthusiastic, successful and prolific club cricketer with Daisy Hill in the Bolton Association who often put up overseas players, such as [[Farokh Engineer]] and [[Javed Miandad]], during Ronnie's childhood.<ref name=\"Irani 2010\"/>\n\n==Domestic career==\n[[Image:Irani and Bopara.jpg|180px|thumb|left|Irani batting against [[Cambridge UCCE]], April 2005]]\nHe started his career playing for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] in 1990, before he moved to [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/2/2357/all_teams.html |title=Teams Ronnie Irani played for |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> At Essex, he gained [[Cult following|cult status]],<ref name=\"ciprof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/15403.html |title=Player Profile: Ronnie Irani |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>  before he became [[Captain (cricket)|captain]] in 2000,<ref name=\"caprof\">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/2/2357/2357.html |title=Player Profile: Ronnie Irani |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> and is generally accepted to have done a decent job in charge, helping to bring through promising players such as [[Alastair Cook]], [[Will Jefferson]] and [[Ravi Bopara]]. After [[Graham Gooch]] stepped down as the club's head coach prior to the start of the 2005 season, Irani assumed some of these responsibilities in addition to his role as county captain.<ref name=\"ciprof\"/>\n\nIn June 2007, he rejected a new contract with [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]] and announced his retirement from first-class cricket at the end of the 2007 season. He retired with immediate effect later that month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/essex/6726287.stm |title=Injury forces Irani's retirement |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 June 2007 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIrani was awarded Fans' player of the series in Natwest Series 2002 featuring India and Sri Lanka for his allround performance. He scored 169 runs and took 8 wickets in the tri-series.\n\n==After retirement==\nAfter his retirement, he took on a position at [[talkSPORT]] in 2007, where he co-hosted, until 2013, ''The Alan Brazil Sports Breakfast'' with former Scottish international footballer [[Alan Brazil]]. On this show, he picked up the nickname Chicken from the dish Chicken Biriyani rhyming with his surname. Following Irani's appointment, the show's audience increased, reaching 1.2 million listeners by May 2008.{{cn|date=January 2020}} During his time at talkSPORT, Irani also appeared as a guest on the BBC quiz show [[A Question of Sport]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronnie Irani|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3354683/|publisher=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Irani's autobiography \"No Boundaries\" was published.<ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/No-Boundaries-Ronnie-Irani/dp/1844548619</ref> He was also  part of a celebrity 'consortium' (along with [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]] DJ [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]]) who clubbed together to pay for [[Paul Gascoigne]] to receive treatment for alcoholism in the US.<ref>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/celebritynews/chris-evans-and-ronnie-irani-help-gazza-get-treatment-8480969.html</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Irani took up the position of Cricket Committee Chairman at Essex and expressed his desire for the club to improve its performances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Essex: Ronnie Irani wants 'massive' improvement|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/33608159|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Irani was quoted as saying that, \u201cWe are still talented and it is great to see young players coming through like Nick Browne, Tom Westley and Jamie Porter. We have to make sure we keep doing that, while getting Essex back to the level that we were in years gone by, knocking on doors and trying to win trophies.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronnie Irani wants Essex CC talent to shine|url=http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Irani-wants-Essex-talent-shine/story-27464264-detail/story.html|publisher=Essex Chronicle|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151207140952/http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Irani-wants-Essex-talent-shine/story-27464264-detail/story.html|archivedate=7 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter having held the position of chairman for several months, Irani said that, \u201cI am really enjoying it. I love Essex Cricket Club and it is a pleasure to work there. The people know and love their cricket and they have always got behind the team as well which is important. It is an exciting time to be part of the club as it is certainly going places and we are more than capable of winning things.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=BIG Interview: Essex chairman Ronnie Irani lifts the lid on his vision for the club|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/sport/13794189.BIG_INTERVIEW__Essex_chairman_Ronnie_Irani_lifts_the_lid_on_his_vision/|publisher=Echo News}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his duties at Essex, Irani is also the co-founder/inventor of OrthoSole,  an orthotic insole that is customizable by the owner, making it considerably more affordable than other RIIAC custom-made alternatives on the market.<ref>{{cite web|title=The OrthoSole Story|url=http://www.orthosole.com/about/the-orthosole-story|publisher=OrthoSole}}</ref>\n\n==Personality==\nHe is known by many sports fans for an \"Exercise Routine\u201d during an England One-Day International in Australia. He was doing a warm-up while fielding, and unbeknown to Irani, the Australian fans were imitating his routine behind his back. When he discovered what they were doing, he played up to the tens of thousands of fans and became quicker as to make the fans carry on even more.<ref name=\"Irani 2010\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZIbcl6RVAiUC&pg=PT18&dq=Jimmy+Irani+father+Ronnie+Bombay+1961 |title=No Boundaries \u2013 Passion and Pain On and Off the Pitch |last=Irani |first=Ronnie |publisher=John Blake Publishing Ltd |format=E-book |year=2010 |accessdate=16 December 2012|isbn=9781843582199 }}</ref><ref>{{youtube|76bL8VsVRwc|Cricket Crowd Mimicking Ronnie Irani's Stretch}}</ref>\n\nIrani is a long time supporter of Manchester United, after being taken to games by his father when he was a child.<ref>{{cite web|title=Q&A: Ronnie Irani|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Fanzone/News-And-Blogs/2009/Oct/QA-Ronnie-Irani.aspx|website=ManUtd.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=15403}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Graham Beecroft]]\n|title=[[TalkSport]] breakfast show host\n''with [[Alan Brazil]]''\n|years=2007\u20132013\n|after=[[Neil Warnock]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{England Squad 2003 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{TalkSport}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Irani, Ronnie}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Essex cricketers]]\n[[Category:Essex cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Lancashire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Leigh, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English people of Parsi descent]]\n[[Category:Irani people]]\n[[Category:First-Class Counties Select XI cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Ronnie Irani\n|               image = Ronnie Irani.jpg\n|             country = England\n|            fullname = Ronald Charles Irani \n|            nickname = Reggie \n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1971|10|26|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], [[Lancashire]], England\n|            heightft = 6\n|          heightinch = 4\n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Right arm [[Medium pace bowling|medium]]\n|       international = true\n|   internationalspan = 1996\u20132003\n|       testdebutdate = 6 June\n|       testdebutyear = 1996\n|    testdebutagainst = India\n|             testcap = 577\n|        lasttestdate = 22 August\n|        lasttestyear = 1999\n|     lasttestagainst = New Zealand\n|        odidebutdate = 23 May\n|        odidebutyear = 1996\n|     odidebutagainst = India\n|              odicap = 137\n|         lastodidate = 26 February\n|         lastodiyear = 2003\n|      lastodiagainst = India\n|            odishirt = 15\n|               club1 = [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]\n|               year1 = 1990\u20131993\n|               club2 = [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]]\n|               year2 = 1994\u20132007\n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|            matches1 = 3\n|               runs1 = 86\n|            bat avg1 = 17.20\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 41\n|         deliveries1 = 192\n|            wickets1 = 3\n|           bowl avg1 = 37.33\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 1/22\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 2/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches2 = 31\n|               runs2 = 360\n|            bat avg2 = 14.40\n|           100s/50s2 = 0/1\n|          top score2 = 53\n|         deliveries2 = 1,283\n|            wickets2 = 24\n|           bowl avg2 = 41.20\n|            fivefor2 = 1\n|             tenfor2 = 0\n|       best bowling2 = 5/26\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 6/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 232\n|               runs3 = 13,472\n|            bat avg3 = 41.58\n|           100s/50s3 = 28/72\n|          top score3 = 218\n|         deliveries3 = 20,389\n|            wickets3 = 339\n|           bowl avg3 = 29.51\n|            fivefor3 = 9\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 6/71\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 79/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 315\n|               runs4 = 7,733\n|            bat avg4 = 30.93\n|           100s/50s4 = 7/46\n|          top score4 = 158[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries4 = 10,453\n|            wickets4 = 309\n|           bowl avg4 = 25.22\n|            fivefor4 = 4\n|             tenfor4 = 0\n|       best bowling4 = 5/26\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 83/\u2013\n|                date = 19 April\n|                year = 2017\n|              source = http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/15403.html Cricinfo\n}}\n'''Ronald Charles  \"Ronnie\" Irani''' (born 26 October 1971<!---in 1971 Leigh was then still part of Lancashire--->) is a former England [[cricket]]er who played Tests and ODIs for England. He played only three [[Test cricket|Tests]] for [[English cricket team|England]], with decidedly mixed success, but found a niche in [[One Day International]]s, where he gained much praise for his performances.\n\nHe spent most of his career at [[Essex County Cricket Club]], latterly as [[captain (cricket)|captain]], after starting at [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]. He is of [[Irani (India)|Irani]] descent, the Iranis being a community of [[Persian people|Persian]] [[Zoroastrian]]s who immigrated to India during the [[British Raj]].\n\nIrani was a genuine [[all-rounder]] until a knee injury in 2003 forced him to stop bowling and play as a specialist batsman. The recurring nature of this injury led to Irani being forced to retire from [[first-class cricket]] in June 2007. At Essex, Irani helped bring through promising players such as [[Alastair Cook]] (England Captain) and [[Ravinder Bopara]] (England Player) as well as winning two major One-Day Titles. Professionally he scored over 20,000 runs and took more than 650 wickets during his career.\n\nHe announced his retirement from first-class cricket at the end of the 2007 season.\n\n==Personal life==\nIrani's father Jimmy Irani arrived in Bolton from Bombay in 1961 to play a summer's club cricket. During that summer he met 16-year-old Lancastrian Anne Main. The two married and had a son, Ronnie. Jimmy Irani was an enthusiastic, successful and prolific club cricketer with Daisy Hill in the Bolton Association who often put up overseas players, such as [[Farokh Engineer]] and [[Javed Miandad]], during Ronnie's childhood.<ref name=\"Irani 2010\"/>\n\n==Domestic career==\n[[Image:Irani and Bopara.jpg|180px|thumb|left|Irani batting against [[Cambridge UCCE]], April 2005]]\nHe started his career playing for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] in 1990, before he moved to [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/2/2357/all_teams.html |title=Teams Ronnie Irani played for |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> At Essex, he gained [[Cult following|cult status]],<ref name=\"ciprof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/15403.html |title=Player Profile: Ronnie Irani |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>  before he became [[Captain (cricket)|captain]] in 2000,<ref name=\"caprof\">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/2/2357/2357.html |title=Player Profile: Ronnie Irani |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> and is generally accepted to have done a decent job in charge, helping to bring through promising players such as [[Alastair Cook]], [[Will Jefferson]] and [[Ravi Bopara]]. After [[Graham Gooch]] stepped down as the club's head coach prior to the start of the 2005 season, Irani assumed some of these responsibilities in addition to his role as county captain.<ref name=\"ciprof\"/>\n\nIn June 2007, he rejected a new contract with [[Essex County Cricket Club|Essex]] and announced his retirement from first-class cricket at the end of the 2007 season. He retired with immediate effect later that month.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/essex/6726287.stm |title=Injury forces Irani's retirement |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 June 2007 |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIrani was awarded Fans' player of the series in Natwest Series 2002 featuring India and Sri Lanka for his allround performance. He scored 169 runs and took 8 wickets in the tri-series.\n\n==After retirement==\nAfter his retirement, he took on a position at [[talkSPORT]] in 2007, where he co-hosted, until 2013, ''The Alan Brazil Sports Breakfast'' with former Scottish international footballer [[Alan Brazil]]. On this show, he picked up the nickname Chicken from the dish Chicken Biriyani rhyming with his surname. Following Irani's appointment, the show's audience increased, reaching 1.2 million listeners by May 2008.{{cn|date=January 2020}} During his time at talkSPORT, Irani also appeared as a guest on the BBC quiz show [[A Question of Sport]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronnie Irani|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3354683/|publisher=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Irani's autobiography \"No Boundaries\" was published.<ref>https://www.amazon.co.uk/No-Boundaries-Ronnie-Irani/dp/1844548619</ref> He was also  part of a celebrity 'consortium' (along with [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]] DJ [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]]) who clubbed together to pay for [[Paul Gascoigne]] to receive treatment for alcoholism in the US.<ref>https://www.standard.co.uk/news/celebritynews/chris-evans-and-ronnie-irani-help-gazza-get-treatment-8480969.html</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Irani took up the position of Cricket Committee Chairman at Essex and expressed his desire for the club to improve its performances.<ref>{{cite web|title=Essex: Ronnie Irani wants 'massive' improvement|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/33608159|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Irani was quoted as saying that, \u201cWe are still talented and it is great to see young players coming through like Nick Browne, Tom Westley and Jamie Porter. We have to make sure we keep doing that, while getting Essex back to the level that we were in years gone by, knocking on doors and trying to win trophies.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronnie Irani wants Essex CC talent to shine|url=http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Irani-wants-Essex-talent-shine/story-27464264-detail/story.html|publisher=Essex Chronicle|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151207140952/http://www.essexchronicle.co.uk/Irani-wants-Essex-talent-shine/story-27464264-detail/story.html|archivedate=7 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter having held the position of chairman for several months, Irani said that, \u201cI am really enjoying it. I love Essex Cricket Club and it is a pleasure to work there. The people know and love their cricket and they have always got behind the team as well which is important. It is an exciting time to be part of the club as it is certainly going places and we are more than capable of winning things.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=BIG Interview: Essex chairman Ronnie Irani lifts the lid on his vision for the club|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/sport/13794189.BIG_INTERVIEW__Essex_chairman_Ronnie_Irani_lifts_the_lid_on_his_vision/|publisher=Echo News}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his duties at Essex, Irani is also the co-founder/inventor of OrthoSole,  an orthotic insole that is customizable by the owner, making it considerably more affordable than other custom-made alternatives on the market.<ref>{{cite web|title=The OrthoSole Story|url=http://www.orthosole.com/about/the-orthosole-story|publisher=OrthoSole}}</ref>\n\n==Personality==\nHe is known by many sports fans for an \"Exercise Routine\u201d during an England One-Day International in Australia. He was doing a warm-up while fielding, and unbeknown to Irani, the Australian fans were imitating his routine behind his back. When he discovered what they were doing, he played up to the tens of thousands of fans and became quicker as to make the fans carry on even more.<ref name=\"Irani 2010\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ZIbcl6RVAiUC&pg=PT18&dq=Jimmy+Irani+father+Ronnie+Bombay+1961 |title=No Boundaries \u2013 Passion and Pain On and Off the Pitch |last=Irani |first=Ronnie |publisher=John Blake Publishing Ltd |format=E-book |year=2010 |accessdate=16 December 2012|isbn=9781843582199 }}</ref><ref>{{youtube|76bL8VsVRwc|Cricket Crowd Mimicking Ronnie Irani's Stretch}}</ref>\n\nIrani is a long time supporter of Manchester United, after being taken to games by his father when he was a child.<ref>{{cite web|title=Q&A: Ronnie Irani|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Fanzone/News-And-Blogs/2009/Oct/QA-Ronnie-Irani.aspx|website=ManUtd.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=15403}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Graham Beecroft]]\n|title=[[TalkSport]] breakfast show host\n''with [[Alan Brazil]]''\n|years=2007\u20132013\n|after=[[Neil Warnock]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{England Squad 2003 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{TalkSport}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Irani, Ronnie}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Essex cricketers]]\n[[Category:Essex cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Lancashire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Leigh, Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:English people of Parsi descent]]\n[[Category:Irani people]]\n[[Category:First-Class Counties Select XI cricketers]]\n", "name_user": "86.178.136.122", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAfter retirement)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronnie_Irani"}
{"title_page": "The Walking Dead (season 10)", "text_new": "{{short description|Season of television series}}\n{{Infobox television season\n |season_number = 10\n |bgcolour      = #A51C36\n |image         = The walking dead season 10 poster.jpg\n |caption       = Promotional poster art featuring characters [[Michonne]], [[Daryl Dixon]] and [[Carol Peletier]]\n |starring      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Norman Reedus]]\n* [[Danai Gurira]]\n* [[Melissa McBride]]\n* [[Christian Serratos]]\n* [[Josh McDermitt]]\n* [[Seth Gilliam]]\n* [[Ross Marquand]]\n* [[Khary Payton]]\n* [[Ryan Hurst]]\n* [[Samantha Morton]]\n* [[Jeffrey Dean Morgan]]\n* [[Callan McAuliffe]]\n* [[Avi Nash]]\n* [[Eleanor Matsuura]]\n* [[Cooper Andrews]]\n* [[Nadia Hilker]]\n* [[Cailey Fleming]]\n* [[Cassady McClincy]]\n* [[Lauren Ridloff]]\n}}\n |country       = United States\n |network       = [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n |first_aired   = {{Start date|2019|10|6}}\n |last_aired    = {{End date|present}}\n |num_episodes  = 15\n |episode_list  = List of The Walking Dead episodes\n}}\n\nThe tenth season of ''[[The Walking Dead (TV series)|The Walking Dead]]'', an American [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[Horror fiction|horror]] [[television series]] on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] premiered on October 6, 2019. The second half of the season premiered on February 23, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://comicbook.com/thewalkingdead/2019/11/25/the-walking-dead-season-10-back-half-premiere-date-february-2020/ |title=The Walking Dead Season 10B Premiere Date Revealed |website=Comicbook.com |first=Brandon |last=Davis |date=November 24, 2019 |accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> Developed for television by [[Frank Darabont]], the series is based on the [[The Walking Dead (comic book)|eponymous series of comic books]] by [[Robert Kirkman]], [[Tony Moore (artist)|Tony Moore]], and [[Charlie Adlard]]. The executive producers are Kirkman, David Alpert, [[Scott M. Gimple]], [[Angela Kang]], [[Greg Nicotero]], Joseph Incaprera, Denise Huth, and [[Gale Anne Hurd]], with Kang as [[showrunner]] for the second consecutive season.<ref name=\"ComicCon\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/walking-dead-season-10-trailer-1225281 |title='Walking Dead' Season 10 Trailer Debuts |first=Josh |last=Wigler |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis season adapts material from issue #145 onward of the comic book series and focuses on the group's preparation and war against the Whisperers. Set several months after the massacre perpetrated by [[Alpha (The Walking Dead)|Alpha]] ([[Samantha Morton]]) during the community fair, the season focuses on the united communities as they initiate a fight in order to end the threat of the Whisperers.\n\nThe tenth season is the final season for series regular [[Danai Gurira]], who has portrayed [[Michonne]] since the [[The Walking Dead (season 3)|third season]].<ref name=\"Danai Gurira\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/walking-dead-danai-gurira-exit-1184189 |title='Walking Dead' Shocker: Danai Gurira to Exit |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 8, 2019 |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"GuriraExit\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2019/07/19/walking-dead-danai-gurira-leaving-show-season-10/ |title=Danai Gurira confirms she is leaving The Walking Dead |first=Dalton |last=Ross |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]}}</ref> The season finale was scheduled to air on April 12, 2020, but post-production was delayed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and the episode will air as a special episode later in 2020.<ref name=\"DeadlineDelay\"/>\n\n==Cast==\n{{Main|List of The Walking Dead (TV series) characters}}\n\n===Main cast===\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| total_width = 300\n| footer    = [[Norman Reedus]] ([[Daryl Dixon]]), [[Danai Gurira]] ([[Michonne]]), and [[Melissa McBride]] ([[Carol Peletier]])\n| image1    = Norman Reedus by Gage Skidmore 4.jpg\n| image2    = Danai Gurira (43606261602) (cropped).jpg\n| image3    = Melissa McBride by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n}} \n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| total_width = 300\n| footer    = [[Christian Serratos]] ([[Rosita Espinosa]]), [[Josh McDermitt]] ([[Eugene Porter]]), and [[Seth Gilliam]] ([[Gabriel Stokes (The Walking Dead)|Gabriel Stokes]])\n| image1    = Christian Serratos by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image2    = Josh McDermitt 2016 (cropped).jpg\n| image3    = Seth Gilliam - Comiccon Brussels 2020 (49677344347) (cropped).jpg\n}} \n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| total_width = 300\n| footer    = [[Ross Marquand]] ([[Aaron (The Walking Dead)|Aaron]]), [[Khary Payton]] ([[King Ezekiel|Ezekiel]]), and [[Ryan Hurst]] ([[Beta (The Walking Dead)|Beta]])\n| image1    = Ross Marquand by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image2    = Khary Payton by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image3    = Ryan Hurst in 2017.jpg\n}} \n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| total_width = 300\n| footer    = [[Samantha Morton]] ([[Alpha (The Walking Dead)|Alpha]]), [[Jeffrey Dean Morgan]] ([[Negan]]), and [[Callan McAuliffe]] ([[Alden (The Walking Dead)|Alden]])\n| image1    = Samantha Morton Edinburgh International Film Festival.png\n| image2    = Jeffrey Dean Morgan by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg\n| image3    = Callan McAuliffe at the Chivas Regal GQ Men of the Year Awards, November 2012.jpg\n}}\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| total_width = 300\n| footer    = [[Avi Nash]] ([[Siddiq (The Walking Dead)|Siddiq]]), [[Eleanor Matsuura]] ([[Yumiko (The Walking Dead)|Yumiko]]), and [[Cooper Andrews]] ([[Jerry (The Walking Dead)|Jerry]])\n| image1    = Avi Nash by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image2    = Eleanor Matsuura by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image3    = Cooper Andrews by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n}}\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| total_width = 300\n| footer    = [[Nadia Hilker]] ([[Magna (The Walking Dead)|Magna]]), [[Cailey Fleming]] (Judith Grimes), and [[Lauren Ridloff]] ([[Connie (The Walking Dead)|Connie]])\n| image1    = Nadia Hilker by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image2    = Cailey Fleming by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| image3    = Lauren Ridloff by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n}}\n\nThe tenth season features nineteen series regulars overall. [[Ryan Hurst]], [[Eleanor Matsuura]], [[Cooper Andrews]], [[Nadia Hilker]], [[Cailey Fleming]], [[Cassady McClincy]], and [[Lauren Ridloff]] were all promoted to series regular status, after previously having recurring roles. Hurst is added to the opening credits, while the rest are credited as \"also starring\".<ref name=\"s10regulars\">{{cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a29121181/walking-dead-season-10-series-regulars/ |title=The Walking Dead season 10 promotes seven stars to series regulars |work=Digital Spy |first=Jess |last=Lee |date=September 19, 2019 |accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Starring====\n* [[Norman Reedus]] as [[Daryl Dixon]], a southerner and Rick's former right-hand man. He is a skilled hunter and a former recruiter for Alexandria.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\">{{cite web |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/a28445232/walking-dead-season-10-release-date/ |title=Walking Dead season 10 premiere date announced by AMC |work=[[Digital Spy]] |first1=Jess |last1=Lee |date=July 19, 2019 |accessdate=July 19, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Danai Gurira]] as [[Michonne]], a katana-wielding warrior and Rick's former romantic partner. She is also adoptive mother to Judith and mother to her and Rick's child.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Melissa McBride]] as [[Carol Peletier]], a survivor who has overcome several traumas, is a skilled and ingenious fighter, and now resides at Alexandria. She is also ex-wife to Ezekiel.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Christian Serratos]] as [[Rosita Espinosa]], a pragmatic member of the group who is mother to her and Siddiq's child. She is also in a relationship with Gabriel.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Josh McDermitt]] as [[Eugene Porter]], an intelligent survivor who has overcome his fear of walkers. He also fell in love with Rosita.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Seth Gilliam]] as [[Gabriel Stokes (The Walking Dead)|Gabriel Stokes]], a priest and head of the council of Alexandria who has reconciled his beliefs with what needs to be done to survive. He is in a relationship with Rosita.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Ross Marquand]] as [[Aaron (The Walking Dead)|Aaron]], a former recruiter from Alexandria who lost his arm in an accident and adoptive father to Gracie.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Khary Payton]] as [[King Ezekiel|Ezekiel]], the charismatic former leader of the Kingdom and ex-husband to Carol.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Ryan Hurst]] as [[Beta (The Walking Dead)|Beta]], the second-in-command of the Whisperers.<ref name=\"s10regulars\"/>\n* [[Samantha Morton]] as [[Alpha (The Walking Dead)|Alpha]], the leader of the Whisperers, a mysterious group of survivors who wear the skins of walkers to mask their presence and the main antagonist of the season.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Jeffrey Dean Morgan]] as [[Negan]], the reformed former leader of the Saviors who is incarcerated at Alexandria. He formed a parental bond with Michonne's adoptive daughter, Judith.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n\n====Also starring====\n* [[Callan McAuliffe]] as [[Alden (The Walking Dead)|Alden]], a former member of the Saviors who resides at the Hilltop and now vows a retaliation against the Whisperers. He is also Enid's former love interest.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Avi Nash]] as [[Siddiq (The Walking Dead)|Siddiq]], a doctor for Alexandria who is the father to his and Rosita's child. He is suffering from PTSD due to being a key witness to Alpha's killings of several members of his group.<ref name=\"DigitalSpy\"/>\n* [[Eleanor Matsuura]] as [[Yumiko (The Walking Dead)|Yumiko]], Magna's girlfriend who's a proficient archer.<ref name=\"s10regulars\"/>\n* [[Cooper Andrews]] as [[Jerry (The Walking Dead)|Jerry]], a former resident of the Kingdom and Ezekiel's right-hand man who is in a relationship with Nabila.<ref name=\"s10regulars\"/>\n* [[Nadia Hilker]] as [[Magna (The Walking Dead)|Magna]], the feisty former leader of a small group of roaming survivors.<ref name=\"s10regulars\"/>\n* [[Cailey Fleming]] as Judith Grimes, the daughter of [[Lori Grimes]] and [[Shane Walsh (The Walking Dead)|Shane Walsh]], and adopted daughter of Rick and Michonne.<ref name=\"s10regulars\"/>\n* [[Cassady McClincy]] as [[Lydia (The Walking Dead)|Lydia]], Alpha's daughter and former Whisperer, who now resides in Alexandria. She is also Henry's former love interest.<ref name=\"s10regulars\"/>\n* [[Lauren Ridloff]] as [[Connie (The Walking Dead)|Connie]], a [[Hearing loss|deaf]] former member of Magna's group who forms a close bond with Daryl.<ref name=\"s10regulars\"/>\n\n===Supporting cast===\n\n====Alexandria Safe-Zone====\n* [[Lindsley Register]] as Laura, a former lieutenant of the Saviors who is a member of the council of Alexandria.\n* [[Kenric Green]] as Scott, a supply runner in Alexandria.\n* Mandi Christine Kerr as Barbara, a resident of Alexandria.\n* Tamara Austin as Nora, a member of the council of Alexandria and Michonne's friend.\n* Anabelle Holloway as Gracie, the adoptive daughter of Aaron.\n* Antony Azor as Rick \"R.J.\" Grimes Jr., the son of Rick and Michonne.\n* Juan Javier Cardenas as Dante, Siddiq's wise-cracking medical assistant and a spy for the Whisperers.\n* Jerri Tubbs as Margo, a former member of the Highwaymen who resents Lydia.\n* David Shae as Alfred, a former member of the Highwaymen and Margo's friend.\n* Blaine Kern III as Brandon, a prison guard in Alexandria who watches over Negan.\n\n====The Hilltop====\n* [[Dan Fogler]] as Luke, a former music teacher who has come to appreciate safety in numbers.\n* Angel Theory as Kelly, Connie's protective sister who has a gradual hearing loss.\n* [[John Finn]] as Earl Sutton, the Hilltop's blacksmith and former husband to Tammy.\n* Nadine Marissa as Nabila, a former resident and gardener of the Kingdom and Jerry's wife.\n* Anthony Lopez as Oscar, a resident of the Hilltop.\n* Gustavo Gomez as Marco, a supply runner of the Hilltop.\n* Kerry Cahill as Dianne, one of Ezekiel's top soldiers and a skilled archer.\n* [[Jackson Pace]] as Gage, a resident of the Hilltop who now resents Lydia over the deaths of his friends.\n\n====Oceanside====\n* [[Sydney Park (actress)|Sydney Park]] as Cyndie, a young woman who is the leader of the Oceanside community.\n* Avianna Mynhier as Rachel Ward, a teenage member of Oceanside, who represents her community.\n* Alex Sgambati as Jules, a member of Oceanside.\n\n====The Whisperers====\n* [[Thora Birch]] as Gamma / Mary, a member of the Whisperers who is very protective of Alpha.<ref name=\"Deadline\"/>\n* Havana Blum as young Lydia.\n* Mark Sivertsen as Rufus, a member of the Whisperers.\n\n====Bloodsworth Island====\n* [[Kevin Carroll (actor)|Kevin Carroll]] as Virgil, a survivor who seeks Michonne's help to look for his family.<ref name=\"Deadline\"/>\n* [[Eve Gordon]] as Celeste, a resident of Bloodsworth Island, who was a researcher alongside Virgil and Jeremiah.\n* [[Taylor Nichols]] as Jeremiah, a resident of Bloodsworth Island, who was a researcher alongside Virgil and Celeste.\n* Olivia Stambouliah as Lucy, a resident of Bloodsworth Island, who was a janitor in the island's research facility.\n\n====Survivor Caravan====\n* [[Breeda Wool]] as Aiden, a member of a survivor caravan.  \n* [[King Bach|Andrew Bachelor]] as Bailey, a member of a survivor caravan and Aiden's friend.\n\n====Miscellaneous====\n* [[Matt Lintz]] as Henry, the adopted son of Carol and Ezekiel who was killed by Alpha in the [[The Walking Dead (season 9)|ninth season]], appears in Carol's hallucinations. He is also Lydia's former love interest.\n* [[Margot Bingham]] as Stephanie, a survivor from an unknown location who communicates with Eugene over the radio.\n* [[Paola L\u00e1zaro]] as Juanita \"Princess\" Sanchez, a quirky and flamboyant survivor.\n* [[Lauren Cohan]] as [[Maggie Greene|Maggie Rhee]], [[Glenn Rhee|Glenn]]'s widow and the former leader of the Hilltop, who left with Georgie and is helping with a new distant community.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/walking-dead-the-tower-showrunner-angela-kang-lauren-cohan-maggie/ |title=The Walking Dead showrunner teases return of Lauren Cohan's Maggie |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |first=Dalton |last=Ross |date=April 5, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CohanReturns\">{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/06/lauren-cohan-returns-the-walking-dead-maggie-finale-trailer-video/ |title=The Walking Dead Finale Trailer Teases the Return of Lauren Cohan as Maggie |website=[[TVLine]] |first=Charlie |last=Mason |date=April 5, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{See also|List of The Walking Dead episodes}}\n<onlyinclude>{{Episode table |background=#A51C36 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=23 |director=16 |writer=27 |writerR=<ref name=\"wga\">{{cite web |url=https://directories.wga.org/project/977873/walking-dead-the |title=The Walking Dead \u2013 WGA Directory |publisher=[[Writers Guild of America West]] |accessdate=January 1, 2020}} Episodes with a credit date in 2019.</ref> |airdate=13 |airdateR=<ref name=\"Futon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/walking-dead/listings/ |title=Shows A-Z - walking dead on amc |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref> |viewers=10 |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list/sublist|The Walking Dead (season 10)\n| EpisodeNumber   = 132\n| EpisodeNumber2  = 1\n| Title           = [[Lines We Cross]]\n| DirectedBy      = [[Greg Nicotero]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Angela Kang]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|6}}\n| Viewers         = 4.00<ref name=\"10.01\">{{cite web |url=https://tvbythe